      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right, science time. No more goblin metaphors, I promise! (Though I suspect even the most dedicated scientist has a tiny, mischievous goblin lurking in their subconscious, just waiting to steal their pipette.)\n\nIf you need to differentiate between iron/manganese lockout (pH issue) and nitrogen deficiency without a lab test, look closely at *where* the yellowing is happening and *how* it looks.\n\n1.  **Nitrogen Deficiency:** This is usually a general, uniform yellowing (chlorosis) that starts on the **oldest, lowest leaves** first. The veins often remain green initially, but the entire leaf tissue fades.\n2.  **Iron/Manganese Deficiency (pH Issue):** This is often characterized by **interveinal chlorosis**, meaning the tissue *between* the veins turns bright yellow, but the veins themselves stay distinctly green. This often appears on **new, young leaves** first, because iron and manganese are mobile in the young growth.\n\nIf the yellowing is primarily on the *new* leaves, lean heavily toward checking your pH first. If it's on the *old* leaves, nitrogen is the prime suspect.\n\nAs for what you can do *right now",
